The annuity is monthly basis; therefore, we will express the rate by dividing the annual percentage rate by twelve months. Hence, we will express the rate in calculation by the following equation:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Rate} &=\dfrac{0.0678}{12}
\end{aligned}$$

Let's now calculate the present value of Baggin's objective one.

$$ \begin{aligned}
PVA &=\$17,500\times\dfrac{1-\dfrac{1}{\left(1+\dfrac{0.0678}{12}\right)^{300}}}{\dfrac{0.0678}{12}}
\\[20pt]
&=\$17,500\times\dfrac{0.815522834}{0.00565}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\$2,525,955.68 }
\end{aligned}$$

As can be seen in our calculation, the present value of objective one is $2,525,955.68.

We will discount the rate in our calculation of the present value by the following equation:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Rate} &=\dfrac{0.0678}{12}
\end{aligned}$$

Let's now calculate the present value of the inheritance using the given from the previous steps.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{PV} &=\dfrac{\$2,000,000}{\left(1 + 0.0678\right)^{300}}
\\[10pt]
&=\dfrac{\$2,000,000}{5.42072508}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\$368,954.33}
\end{aligned}$$

Based on our calculation, the present value of Baggin's third objective is $368,954.33.

Next, combine the present value of the annuity and the present value of the inheritance to determine the total required post-retirement amount. We will use the following formula.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Post-Retirement Total Amount Required} &= \text{PV of Annuity}+\text{PV of inheritance}
\end{aligned}$$

Where:

$PV$, which refers to the present value

We will express the rate in our calculation as the below equation as the annuity is monthly base:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Rate} &=\dfrac{0.0957}{12}
\end{aligned}$$

Let's now calculate the future value of Baggin's savings for ten years for the cabin.

$$ \begin{aligned}
FVA &=\$2,350\times\dfrac{\left(1+\dfrac{0.0957}{12}\right)^{120}-1}{\dfrac{0.0957}{12}}
\\[25pt]
&=\$2,350\times\dfrac{1.594007898}{0.007975}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\$469,707.66}
\end{aligned}$$

As can be seen in our calculation, Baggins saving after ten years is $469,707.66.

Next, calculate the amount remaining from his pre-retirement savings since Baggin's savings are greater after ten years than the cabin's cost. Our calculation can be summarized in the following equation:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Amount Remaining} &= \text{FV of Savings}-\text{Cost of Cabin}
\end{aligned}$$

Next, since the period base in our calculation is monthly, we will express the rate in the following equation:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Rate} &=\dfrac{0.0957}{12}
\end{aligned}$$

Let's now calculate the future value of the amount remaining.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{FV} &=\$124,707.66\times\left(1 + \dfrac{0.0957}{12}\right)^{240}
\\[10pt]
&=\$124,707.66\times6.728876974
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\$839,142.48}
\end{aligned}$$

Hence, the future value of Baggin's savings is $839,142.48.
